{"parse":{"title":"Four corners of the world","pageid":8457663,"revid":856360394,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For other uses, see <a href=\"/wiki/Four_corners_of_the_world_(disambiguation)\" class=\"mw-disambig\" title=\"Four corners of the world (disambiguation)\">Four corners of the world (disambiguation)</a>.</div>\n<div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">See also: <a href=\"/wiki/Four_continents\" title=\"Four continents\">Four continents</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Biblical_cosmology\" title=\"Biblical cosmology\">Biblical cosmology</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Flat_Earth\" title=\"Flat Earth\">Flat Earth</a></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Earth_symbol.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Earth_symbol.svg/220px-Earth_symbol.svg.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"220\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Earth_symbol.svg/330px-Earth_symbol.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Earth_symbol.svg/440px-Earth_symbol.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"50\" data-file-height=\"50\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Earth_symbol.svg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The astronomical symbol of <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\" title=\"Earth\">Earth</a> represents either the four quadrants of the world or the <a href=\"/wiki/Four_continents\" title=\"Four continents\">four continents</a>.</div></div></div>\n<p>Several <a href=\"/wiki/Cosmology\" title=\"Cosmology\">cosmological</a> and mythological systems portray <b>four corners of the world</b> or <b>four quarters of the world</b> corresponding approximately to the four <a href=\"/wiki/Points_of_the_compass\" title=\"Points of the compass\">points of the compass</a> (or the two solstices and two equinoxes). At the center may lie a sacred mountain, garden, <a href=\"/wiki/World_tree\" title=\"World tree\">world tree</a>, or other beginning-point of creation. Often <a href=\"/wiki/Four_rivers\" class=\"mw-disambig\" title=\"Four rivers\">four rivers</a><sup class=\"plainlinks noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"vertical-align:text-top;white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://dispenser.info.tm/~dispenser/cgi-bin/dab_solver.py?page=Four_corners_of_the_world&amp;editintro=Template:Disambiguation_needed/editintro&amp;client=Template:Dn\"><span title=\"Link needs disambiguation. (August 2018)\">disambiguation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> run to the four corners of the world, and water or irrigate the four quadrants of the Earth.\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Cosmological_Diagram._Aluvihara,_Sri_Lanka_0475.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Cosmological_Diagram._Aluvihara%2C_Sri_Lanka_0475.jpg/220px-Cosmological_Diagram._Aluvihara%2C_Sri_Lanka_0475.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Cosmological_Diagram._Aluvihara%2C_Sri_Lanka_0475.jpg/330px-Cosmological_Diagram._Aluvihara%2C_Sri_Lanka_0475.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Cosmological_Diagram._Aluvihara%2C_Sri_Lanka_0475.jpg/440px-Cosmological_Diagram._Aluvihara%2C_Sri_Lanka_0475.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2592\" data-file-height=\"1944\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Cosmological_Diagram._Aluvihara,_Sri_Lanka_0475.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Tibetan conception of four rivers dividing the world into quadrants</div></div></div>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Christianity\" title=\"Christianity\">Christianity</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Judaism\" title=\"Judaism\">Judaism</a>, the Old Testament (<a href=\"https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Bible_(King_James)/Genesis#2:8\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"s:Bible (King James)/Genesis\">Genesis 2:8-14</a>) identifies the <a href=\"/wiki/Garden_of_Eden\" title=\"Garden of Eden\">Garden of Eden</a>, and the four rivers as the <a href=\"/wiki/Tigris\" title=\"Tigris\">Tigris</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Euphrates\" title=\"Euphrates\">Euphrates</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Pishon\" title=\"Pishon\">Pishon</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Gihon\" title=\"Gihon\">Gihon</a>. The Tigris runs to <a href=\"/wiki/Assyria\" title=\"Assyria\">Assyria</a>, the Euphrates to <a href=\"/wiki/Armenia\" title=\"Armenia\">Armenia</a>, the Pishon to <a href=\"/wiki/Havilah\" title=\"Havilah\">Havilah</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Elam\" title=\"Elam\">Elam</a>, and the Gihon to <a href=\"/wiki/Aethiopia\" title=\"Aethiopia\">Ethiopia</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-George_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-George-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Mesopotamian_mythology\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mesopotamian mythology\">Mesopotamian cosmology</a>, four rivers flowing out of the garden of creation, which is the center of the world, define the four corners of the world.<sup id=\"cite_ref-George_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-George-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  From the point of view of the <a href=\"/wiki/Akkadian_Empire\" title=\"Akkadian Empire\">Akkadians</a>, the northern geographical horizon was marked by <a href=\"/wiki/Subartu\" title=\"Subartu\">Subartu</a>, the west by <a href=\"/wiki/Amorites\" title=\"Amorites\"><span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">Mar.tu</span></a>, the east by <a href=\"/wiki/Elam\" title=\"Elam\">Elam</a> and the south by <a href=\"/wiki/Sumer\" title=\"Sumer\">Sumer</a>; later rulers of all of Mesopotamia, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Cyrus_the_Great\" title=\"Cyrus the Great\">Cyrus</a>, claimed among their titles <i><i lang=\"akk-Latn\" title=\"Akkadian-language transliteration\"><a href=\"/wiki/Lugal\" title=\"Lugal\">LUGAL</a> kib-ra-a-ti er-b\u00e9-et-t\u00ec</i></i>, \"King of the Four Quarters\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Hinduism\" title=\"Hinduism\">Hinduism</a>, the sacred mountain <a href=\"/wiki/Mount_Kailash\" title=\"Mount Kailash\">Kailash</a> has four sides, from which four rivers flow to the four quarters of the world (the <a href=\"/wiki/Ganges\" title=\"Ganges\">Ganges</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Indus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Indus\">Indus</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Oxus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Oxus\">Oxus</a> (Amu Darya), and <a href=\"/wiki/%C5%9Aita_River\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"\u015aita River\">\u015aita</a> (Tarim)), dividing the world into four quadrants. Another account portrays a celestial mountain, <a href=\"/wiki/Mount_Meru\" title=\"Mount Meru\">Mount Meru</a>, buttressed by four terrestrial mountain ranges which extend in four directions. Between them lie four sacred lakes, through which the celestial river divides into four earthly rivers, which flow to the four corners and irrigate the four quadrants of the Earth. <a href=\"/wiki/Buddhism\" title=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Bon_religion\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bon religion\">Bon religion</a> of Tibet have similar accounts.<sup id=\"cite_ref-George_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-George-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Four_corners_of_the_world&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-George-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-George_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-George_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-George_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">George &amp; George (2014) <i>The Mythology of Eden</i>, Rowman &amp; Littlefield</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation book\"><a href=\"/wiki/Richard_D._Nelson\" title=\"Richard D. Nelson\">Nelson, Richard D.</a> (2006). \"Babes in the Wood\". <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=3AK8YTfH-AEC\"><i>From Eden to Babel: An Adventure in Bible Study</i></a>. St. Louis, Missouri: Chalice Press. p.&#160;26. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780827210776\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780827210776\">9780827210776</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2016-05-20</span></span>. <q>The four rivers flowing out to the four corners of the world explain global geography as the ancients would have pictured it ([Genesis] 2:10-14).</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Babes+in+the+Wood&amp;rft.btitle=From+Eden+to+Babel%3A+An+Adventure+in+Bible+Study&amp;rft.place=St.+Louis%2C+Missouri&amp;rft.pages=26&amp;rft.pub=Chalice+Press&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.isbn=9780827210776&amp;rft.aulast=Nelson&amp;rft.aufirst=Richard+D.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D3AK8YTfH-AEC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFour+corners+of+the+world\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation book\"><a href=\"/wiki/James_B._Jordan\" title=\"James B. Jordan\">Jordan, James B.</a> (1999). \"Sociology: A Biblico-Historical Approach\". <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=33lKAwAAQBAJ\"><i>The Sociology of the Church: Essays in Reconstruction</i></a> (reprint ed.). Eugene, Oregon: Wipf and Stock Publishers. p.&#160;86. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781579102487\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9781579102487\">9781579102487</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2016-05-20</span></span>. <q>In a generally ignored but all-important paragraph of Genesis 2, we are told how the world was organized when it was created [...]. In short, the world was organized in terms of a primordial duality between the central sanctuary of Eden, and the outlying world watered by four rivers extending to the four corners of the world.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Sociology%3A+A+Biblico-Historical+Approach&amp;rft.btitle=The+Sociology+of+the+Church%3A+Essays+in+Reconstruction&amp;rft.place=Eugene%2C+Oregon&amp;rft.pages=86&amp;rft.edition=reprint&amp;rft.pub=Wipf+and+Stock+Publishers&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.isbn=9781579102487&amp;rft.aulast=Jordan&amp;rft.aufirst=James+B.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D33lKAwAAQBAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFour+corners+of+the+world\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http://www.binujohn.name/2013/04/14/the-four-quarters-of-the-world/\">[1]</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2227\nCached time: 20180921191435\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.236 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.303 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 376/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 8930/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 906/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 11/40\nExpensive parser function count: 1/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 4302/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.167/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 9.75 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  274.303      1 -total\n 47.29%  129.715      1 Template:Transl\n 23.65%   64.873      1 Template:Reflist\n 17.90%   49.111      2 Template:Cite_book\n 13.33%   36.562      1 Template:Dn\n 10.91%   29.936      1 Template:Fix\n  9.59%   26.318      2 Template:Category_handler\n  8.38%   22.974      1 Template:Other_uses\n  2.91%    7.970      1 Template:Bibleverse\n  2.13%    5.852      1 Template:See_also\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:8457663-0!canonical and timestamp 20180921191434 and revision id 856360394\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"All_articles_with_links_needing_disambiguation"},{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Articles_with_links_needing_disambiguation_from_August_2018"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Mythological_cosmologies"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Physical_geography"},{"sortkey":"Corners of the world","*":"4_(number)"}],"links":[{"ns":14,"exists":"","*":"Category:Articles with links needing disambiguation